How is it submitted?
You will upload a tar file to the elearn website.
You will then download it, untar it, and verify that it has no errors in
how you tarred it. If we cannot untar your file, you just get a zero, no
questions asked.
What I mean is: It's YOUR job to upload correctly and to test it, NOT the TA's.


What is submitted?
A file named PA1.tar
This file will not contain filesystem.tar, but will instead contain your code,
which will include a command to untar from ~/filesystem.tar (ie, the file will
be on the TA's computer, not your computer. And what that means is that your
code to add the links for coconut and coconuts will be added in your code, not
in the file system itself.)
Your file will contain all other files you need to run, and those files need
to be accessed through relative addressing. (What I mean is: the TA's computer
is not your computer. Her user name is not your user name. If you use absolute
addressing, then the paths will be wrong on her computer.)


What are the rules?
1. You may only use unix commands that we have learned. And you may not use AWK.

2. You must use cshell.
   The main file you'll have is a script named dunnet. And line 1 will read as:
   % head -1 dunnet
   #!/usr/bin/csh
   (Also allowed: #!/usr/bin/tcsh,  #!/bin/csh, or  #!/bin/tcsh.)

   To be clear: the cshell script will use "echo -n \>;set command = $<:q", in
   order to achieve the command prompt of the dunnet game.

3. No group work or sharing code. You can discuss the assignment, but you cannot
   let others see your code or tell others what to write. If caught, BOTH the
   copier and the one copied from will fail.

4. Limit your AI usage. The AI can be a helpful tool for understanding the
   assignment (so long as you remember that it does make mistakes).
   The AI can also be abused, as you use it to do your work for you, without
   you even understanding what it is doing.
   There are certain indicators that can be detected if you simply tell the
   AI to do the assignment for you. If these indicators are detected, then you
   will get a 0. What I mean is: You can use the AI to help you; you cannot use
   the AI to write your code.

5. These are the only commands you need to implement:
   basic commands:
     i, get, drop, dig, type, x (for examining objects only), l (for looking at
     the room's description only), exit (which has two meanings, depending on
     if typing in the pokey computer), and put (which requires also saying "in",
     and which has a variety of potential error messages.)
   compute commands in pokey:
     cat, cd, ls, pwd, uncompress, exit
   direction commands:
     u, d, n, s, e, w, ne, nw, se, sw
   You do not need to implement any actions that result in player death.

6. You must make meaningful use of the data in filesystem.tar whenever possible.
   What this means is that you cannot type into your program hard-coded text
   that could have been obtained from the contents of files you already have.

7. You must use a Cshell array variable to track visited rooms.

8. You must make use of intelligent wildcard and regular expression patterns.
   As described below points are based on the length of the patterns used.

9. When the objects in a room are listed at the entering of the room, the order
   in which they list is NOT a requirement of this assignment.

10. The TA can test other error messages beyond the ones demonstrated in the
    provided walkthroughs. You should match the actual game behavior exactly
    in every case.
    

