To know if the person has attempted to use a valid object name (perhaps not in
a valid location, but at least a valid object name), you want a pattern that
matches to all of the above, but not to the other files that can be inside of
/rooms:
hidden files, description, e, n, ne, nw, s, se, sw, and w

Aim for a minimum size wildcard pattern (or set of patterns if necessary).
Points will be assigned based on the length of your pattern.

Then when trying to get an object, these are .o files, with the exception of
boulder.o and bear.o. You need a single wildcard pattern for this.
Points will be assigned based on the length of your pattern.

When trying to examine an object, remember that it can be in either your
room (pokey/room/<roomname>) or in your inventory (pokey/usr/toukmond).

When implementing get all, you need to make the text look correct by sending
the matched filenames (of getable objects) into a sed one-liner.

When entering a room, you cd to the link, and then display the room's
description (and when relevant, also .panels.description -- this special
case is to be achieved with using a proper wildcard pattern to cat, so
that both descriptions display).

When you enter a room, the .o objects in the room have display messages,
and you must display these using: ls --color=never *.o | sed '...'.
The order in which they print is unimportant, but the text itself must
exactly match the real game.

When you reenter room, it only displays the first line of the display file.
This must be handled through a Cshell array variable that tracks visited
rooms.

When you try to go in a wrong direction, you get the proper message.
When you try to enter the house without the key in your inventory, you
get the proper message. When you get or drop the key, the permissions on
the hallway directory change accordingly.

When you get or drop an item with alternate names, those names will all
go into the inventory, but they don't display messages, or show up when
you say "i", or when you look in pokey/usr/toukmond. That is because you
either ignore them because they are links or because your wildcard pattern
excludes them.


